Fresh-eyes review complete. I reviewed `src/blog/people/drafts/Kiernan-Shipka.md` and appended a `FRESH EYES REVIEW (2026-07-11)` comment block at the bottom of the file (no body edits made, per the command).

The two biggest issues flagged:

1. **Longlegs is missing from the body entirely.** It's in the frontmatter `knows_about` but never mentioned in the article — and it's not just a filmography gap. Oz Perkins, whose "flip the switch" quote anchors the draft's best section, re-cast her a decade after Blackcoat's Daughter as Carrie Anne Camera, a catatonic survivor whose five-minute scene was widely called the film's creepiest. That role is pure un-composure — the strongest available rebuttal to the IndieWire "too polished" critique — and I suggested landing it as the closer of the "poised" section, converting that section from defense into trajectory.

2. **The central irony repeats too often.** The "everything turns back into professional development" move lands at least four times in the same shape ("reports to the machine," "the feelings file a report," the Forbes riff, "she caters it"). It's the spine of the piece, but by the fourth pass the reader notices the writer's move instead of her. Related duplicates: the mentor's assignment is spent twice (diagnosis + pull-quote section), and the 5 a.m. lasagna appears near-verbatim in both the diagnosis and the Rabbit Hole.

Also noted: the "get your heart broken" setup never gets cashed out romantically, the 2020–2023 career gap makes the second-adolescence section read like four years of dinners, and the ending, the Sally timeline, and the Perdomo restraint are keepers the next pass should preserve.

Sources: [Collider on Shipka's Longlegs scene](https://collider.com/longlegs-kiernan-shipka/), [Crooked Marquee — "The Year of Kiernan Shipka"](https://crookedmarquee.com/growing-up-onscreen-the-year-of-kiernan-shipka/)
